ESM 206 Assignment 4 - Spiny Lobsters

Alex Ehrens & Courtney Krone

11/11/2019

1. Introduction

The California spiny lobster (Panulirus interruptus) is an important species along the Southern California coast and plays a key role in maintaining diversity in kelp forests. These lobsters are a common target for fishermen, which greatly affects their size and abundance in the kelp forest ecosystems. This report explores the relationship between the size and abundance distribution of the California spiny lobster at five locations along the Santa Barbara channel. Of the five sites, two are designated marine protected areas (MPAs), which restrict human activity —including fishing. Many MPAs have shown positive trends of recovery in habitats across the world. This report hopes to answer the question of whether MPAs affect the California spiny lobster size and abundance along the Santa Barbara coast. This will help assess the recovery of the kelp forest ecosystem.

2. Data and Methods

The two variables being analyzed in this report are lobster size (mm) and lobster abundance at five sites along the Santa Barbara channel between years 2012-2018. Welch’s two sample t-test was used to compare lobster size at MPA and non-MPA sites for 2012 and 2018. The following scenarios were compared:

  • 2012 MPA vs.2012 Non-MPA
  • 2018 MPA vs. 2018 Non-MPA
  • 2012 MPA vs. 2018 MPA
  • 2012 Non-MPA vs. 2018 Non-MPA

A 95% significance level was used. Rstudio Version 1.2.1335 was used to analyze data and run these statistical tests.

3. Results

a. Results A

IVEE and NAPL - MPA

AQUE, CARP and MOHK - Non-MPA

  • Need to change color and show between MPA and NonMPA sites

In general, the total lobster abundance at each of the 5 survey sites have increased from 2012 to 2018. However, the only two sites to show an increase in abundance over the final year of study (2017 to 2018) are Isla Vista and Naples, both of these sites are located in Marine Protected Areas. The three sites that are not in Marine Protected Areas show a decrease in total lobster abundance over the final year of the survey. It appears from the trends in Figure 1 that designated Marine Protected Areas help improve lobster abundance in those areas.

b. Results B

The density plots above show each sites distribution of lobster sizes (mm) in 2012 and 2018. The two MPA sites, Isla Vista and Naples, show a positive shift in lobster size distribution in 2018 compared to 2012. However, the non-MPA sites, Arroyo Quemado, Mohawk and Carpinteria, show little to no shifts in lobster size distribution. Based on these graphs, the lobster populations are able to grow larger which may indicate they are healthier and living longer due to reduced fishing and a flourishing habitat.

Results C notes (DELETE LATER)

MPA vs. Non-MPA in 2012:

  • Diff. in means = (74.92 - 67.38) = 7.54
  • Non-MPA > MPA
  • t = -3.2516, p-value = 0.002263
  • Cohen’s d = -0.6098605 (medium)

MPA vs. Non-MPA in 2018:

  • Diff. in means = (77.57 - 73.62) = 3.95
  • MPA > Non-MPA
  • t = 7.3071, p-value = 4.876e-13
  • Cohen’s d = 0.3514986 (small)

MPA in 2012 vs. MPA in 2018:

  • Diff. in means = (77.57 - 67.38) = 10.19.
  • Increase in mean size from 2012 to 2018
  • t = -4.6879, p-value = 4.76e-05
  • Cohen’s d = -0.8700026 (large)

Non-MPA in 2012 vs. Non-MPA in 2018:

  • Diff. in means = (74.92 - 73.62) = 1.30
  • Small decrease in mean size from 2012 to 2018
  • t = 1.3343, p-value = 0.1831
  • Cohen’s d = 0.1213778 (negligible)
Results C write-up

MPA sites are typically chosen at spots that have the best chance of restoring the bounty of ocean life. The abundance in these areas may have attracted many fishermen to fish in that area causing lobster abundance and size to be very low in these areas.

MPA vs. Non-MPA in 2012

The differences between mean lobster sizes between MPA vs. Non-MPA sites in 2012 is larger with Non-MPA sites having larger mean lobster sizes and a medium effect size. A relatively large p-value of 0.002263 was also calculated. This could potentially mean that MPA sites were fished heavily compared to Non-MPA before it became a designated protected area.

MPA vs. Non-MPA in 2018

Null hypothesis: There is no difference in the mean lobster size for MPA vs. Non-MPA sites for 2018. Alternative hypothesis: There is a difference in mean lobster size for MPA vs. Non-MPA sites for 2018. The difference in means between MPA vs. Non-MPA during 2018 is 3.95 with a small effect size. A small p-value of 4.876 x10^-13 was also calculated. This means that the probability of the null hypothesis being true is very small.

MPA in 2012 vs. MPA in 2018

Null hypothesis: There is no difference between the mean lobster size of MPA sites for 2012 and MPA sites in 2018. Alternative hypothesis: There is a difference between mean lobster sizes for MPA sites for 2012 and MPA sites in 2018. The difference in means between MPA sites in 2012 and MPA sites in 2018 is larger with a large effect size. A small p-value 4.76 x10^-5 was also calculated. This means that the probability of the null hypothesis being true is very small.

Non-MPA in 2012 vs. Non-MPA in 2018

Null hypothesis: There is no difference between mean lobster size of Non-MPA sites for 2012 and Non-MPA sites in 2018. Alternative hypothesis: There is a difference between mean lobster size of Non-MPA sites for 2012 and Non-MPA sites in 2018.
